'''Throw a Sickie''' is New Zealand slang meaning to have a day off from work, supposedly because of ill health.   It is used in two senses.  Genuininely, when someone really is sick.   Ironically, when someone has called in sick but that is merely an excuse for just having a day off.

The term sickie is also widely used in Australia.  It may typically be termed as throwing a sickie.  The usual circumstances will be for a worker to phone their place of work, either the day before or on the morning when they are due to attend work.  The worker will typically feign some sort of illness, sounding unwell and explaining which misfortune has beset them.  Sickies are often attributed to a big night of alcohol consumption the day before, desire for a long weekend and also conflict in the workplace.  The [[Australian Prime Minister]] [[Bob Hawke]] once famously stated, "Any boss who sacks a worker for not coming to work today is a bum!".  This comment was made on the morning of [[26 September, 1983]] after the yacht [[Australia II]] had won the [[America's Cup]] from the United States Stars and Stripes for the first time in the then 132 year history of the yachting race.  At the time (early in the morning) Bob Hawke was wearing a garish jacket and being showered in [[sparkling white wine]].

